  "faqQ1": "Where do these numbers come from?",
  "faqA1": "The device by the entrance detects the WiFi signals of passing phones and counts them as anonymous visits. It can't see who they are or what the phone is doing.",
  "faqQ2": "Why is it a trend, not an exact counter?",
  "faqA2": "Not everyone has WiFi on, and some phones are seen several times. The numbers give a reliable picture of footfall and how it changes over time, not a person-by-person total.",
  "faqQ3": "What exactly does the device see?",
  "faqA3": "Only anonymous, momentary WiFi signal identifiers — turned into stats immediately. No phone numbers, names, locations or history.",
  "faqQ4": "What do we NOT collect?",
  "faqA4": "No personal data. Nothing goes to the cloud or the internet — stats live only on this phone. No cameras, no recordings.",
  "faqQ5": "What if the numbers look odd?",
  "faqA5": "Check that the device has power and a good spot by the entrance. Small numbers in quiet periods are normal — we then show only the day's summary.",
  "faqQ6": "How long is data kept?",
  "faqA6": "Two different things, two different answers. Raw observations on the SD card delete themselves after 30 days — that's a hard limit in the device, not a setting. The statistics themselves (daily and hourly summaries) are kept indefinitely, both on the card and on your phone. They can be kept forever because they're just numbers: there's no identifier in them, so they aren't personal data.",
  "faqQ7": "What does the \"<5\" badge mean?",
  "faqA7": "That fewer than 5 people were seen in that hour, so we deliberately don't show it on its own. With numbers that small someone could tie the result to a specific person (\"at 7am it was only the postman\"). The hour isn't lost — it still counts toward the day's total.",
  "faqQ8": "Why does the hourly chart have gaps?",
  "faqA8": "Two reasons. First, hours with fewer than 5 people aren't published separately (see above). Second, the device only backfills the last 7 days of hourly detail — for older days you only have the hours when your phone happened to be connected. Daily totals are always complete.",
  "faqQ9": "The device lost power — what about the data?",
  "faqA9": "The data is safe on the SD card. The clock is the problem: the device has no battery-backed clock, so after a longer outage it may think it's an earlier date and misdate new records. Just connect with your phone — the app sets the clock automatically on every connection.",
  "faqQ10": "How many phones can pair, and how do I add one?",
  "faqA10": "Three at a time. A fourth phone pushes out the oldest one, which then has to pair again. To add a phone: short-press the button on the device (the LED starts blinking cyan — you have 60 seconds) and pair from the app.",
  "faqQ11": "My phone won't connect — what now?",
  "faqA11": "The pairing is stored on both sides, and sometimes one side loses its half; then the device and the phone can't agree. Fix it like this: in the app go to Settings → Forget device (this also removes the system pairing), then on the device hold the button from the moment you power it on for about 3 seconds — the LED blinks magenta and then goes solid magenta briefly. That means the device wiped all its pairings. Now pair again.",
  "faqQ12": "What's the button for, and what do the LED colours mean?",
  "faqA12": "Button: short click = open pairing (60s). Hold 3s = add a phone to the background list. Hold 10s = restart. Hold from power-on = wipe pairings.\n\nLED:\n• red→green→blue→white at startup — LED self-test\n• slow blue blink — idle, all good\n• cyan — pairing window open\n• breathing blue — sending data to your phone\n• fast amber — waiting for a phone to add to the background list\n• red, speeding up — you're holding the button, restart is coming\n• white flash, then 3s dark — restarting\n• magenta — wiping pairings",
  "faqQ13": "Is this an exact headcount?",
  "faqA13": "No, and we don't pretend otherwise. Modern phones randomise their address every few minutes to protect their owner's privacy — which works against us too. Our fingerprint is steadier than the address alone, but some phones still manage to \"change coats\", which typically undercounts returning visitors by 10–30%. Trends (is today busier than last Tuesday) are reliable — treat the absolute numbers as a good estimate, not a turnstile.",
  "faqQ14": "I'm moving the device to another location — what should I do?",
  "faqA14": "Technically nothing — move it and plug it in. But the history doesn't reset: data from the old place stays and mixes with the new, so \"this Tuesday vs a normal Tuesday\" comparisons will mislead until a few weeks of the new location build up. Staff at the new place will land on the background list by themselves, after about 6 hours.",
  "faqQ15": "Are staff and family inflating my numbers?",
  "faqA15": "The device filters them out by itself. If a phone is around for 6 different hours across a shift and actually generates traffic, it lands on the \"background devices\" list and stops counting as a customer. You can see how many there are on the device screen. You can also add a phone by hand: hold the button for 3 seconds (the LED flashes amber) and within 30 seconds hold the phone right next to the device.",
